article.headline: Chicago St. 79, Oakland, Mich. 78
article.story: ROCHESTER, Mich. (AP) -- Kourtney Calvin's layup with 2.6 seconds left gave Chicago State a 79-78 nonconference victory over Oakland on Saturday night. After Derick Nelson put Oakland up 78-77 with a put-back with 9.7 seconds to play, Royce Parran drove the length of the court before finding Calvin open under the basket. Parran then intercepted Rick Billings' court-length pass as time expired. The undersized Cougars (6-14) trailed 47-30 with 16 minutes to play, but took over the game with a full-court press. The Golden Grizzlies (8-9) turned the ball over 13 times during the Chicago State comeback. Michael Henderson led Chicago State with 20 points, while Parran had 18 points and 11 rebounds. Oakland center Shawn Hopes dominated the second half, but it wasn't enough. The 6-7, 275-pound senior matched a career best with 22 points and added a career-high 15 rebounds. The Cougars went ahead 75-74 on two Calvin free throws with 2:05 to play. After the teams traded turnovers and missed shots, Hopes put the Grizzlies up with two foul shots. Parran answered with an off-balance bank shot with 23 seconds to go, and that appeared to be enough when Brandon Cassise missed a 3-pointer. Nelson, though, grabbed his 10th rebound and scored for what turned out to be a short-lived lead.
